4. REPOSITORY GOVERNANCE AND PRODUCTION ACCESS

4.1 Production branch. The `master` branch is the production branch. Only the
    Maintainer may merge into `master`, either directly or by approving and
    merging pull requests. No other person may merge to `master` unless the
    Rights Holder has given them explicit written Maintainer authorization.

4.2 Development branch. Day-to-day work may occur on `feature` or other branches
    named by the Maintainer. Merging into `master` always requires Maintainer
  review and approval.

4.3 Deployments. Production deployments (e.g. Vercel production environment)
    must track `master` and may only be triggered or approved by the Maintainer.
    Credentials, environment variables, and infrastructure access are restricted
    to the Maintainer unless explicitly delegated in writing.

4.4 Future contributors. The Rights Holder may invite Contributors under terms
    set out in writing (e.g. Contributor License Agreement). Until such terms
    are agreed:
    (a) Contributors may fork or branch only for purposes authorized by the
        Maintainer;
    (b) Pull requests do not grant merge rights; the Maintainer decides what
        is accepted and when it reaches `master`;
    (c) Accepted contributions become part of the Project owned by the Rights
        Holder, unless otherwise agreed in writing.

4.5 Revocation. The Rights Holder may revoke Maintainer or Contributor access at
    any time. Revoked persons must immediately cease merging, deploying, or
    using non-public materials.

